{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658116"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:42:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:42:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20710"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20710"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.96,0,0,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96906"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13586"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79521"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10956"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"12588"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32663"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96906"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic inflammation is a prolonged inflammatory response that can persist for weeks to years.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanism that leads to chronic inflammation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Persistent infection with intracellular pathogens","Repeated acute vascular injury","Excessive neutrophil activation","Impaired phagocyte migration","Defective complement cascade"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Epersistent infection with intracellular pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E. Chronic inflammation commonly develops when the immune system cannot effectively eliminate certain microorganisms, particularly those that can survive within cells. Examples include mycobacteria, fungi, and some viruses. These infections often trigger granulomatous inflammation through delayed-type hypersensitivity responses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeated acute vascular injury\u003C/strong\u003E - While vascular damage can contribute to inflammation, it is not a primary mechanism of chronic inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive neutrophil activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Neutrophils are predominantly involved in acute rather than chronic inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired phagocyte migration\u003C/strong\u003E - This would actually reduce inflammatory responses rather than cause chronic inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefective complement cascade\u003C/strong\u003E - Complement deficiencies typically lead to reduced rather than chronic inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic inflammation is characterised by the presence of mononuclear cells (lymphocytes, plasma cells, and macrophages) rather than neutrophils, and can also be triggered by autoimmune conditions or persistent exposure to toxic agents.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic inflammation can arise from persistent infections, autoimmune diseases, or toxic exposures.","Persistent infections with organisms like mycobacteria and fungi commonly trigger chronic granulomatous inflammation.","The inability of the immune system to eliminate certain pathogens leads to ongoing inflammatory responses."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 96"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79521"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:52:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:53:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13586"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96906"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10956"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Chronic inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12588"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Mechanisms of chronic inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"